{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e443abf-9185-496c-b31b-73bb70894d0d","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform .NET diagnostics tool and requires no install beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (uses the cpu-sampling profile by default)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need deeper OS-level detail:\n\nUse **PerfView** (free Microsoft tool) which captures ETW traces:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\n### When to pick which:\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Managed-code CPU sampling, quick & lightweight |\n| PerfView | Full ETW traces, GC analysis, OS-level stacks, mixed managed/native |\n\n**Start with `dotnet-trace`** — it's simpler. Escalate to PerfView if you need native frames or kernel-level context (e.g., lock contention, I/O waits).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2a4868db-9144-451b-a679-56c841fba5d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":410,"requestId":"9812:F7FBE:C61E7E:E70E71:69F4018A"},"id":"02eb4881-91d9-4f5d-923f-b0ec5b60460e","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:27:49.420Z","parentId":"0c1dc618-1517-4400-992e-151de8aa825b"}
